ğŸ”¹ What is Promise.allSettled?

It takes an array of promises (just like Promise.all).

But difference:

âœ… It waits for all promises to finish (whether resolved or rejected).

Instead of failing on the first rejection, it gives a detailed result for each promise.

ğŸ”¹ Syntax
Promise.allSettled([promise1, promise2, promise3])
  .then(results => console.log(results));

ğŸ”¹ Example
let p1 = Promise.resolve("âœ… Success 1");
let p2 = Promise.reject("âŒ Failed 2");
let p3 = Promise.resolve("âœ… Success 3");

Promise.allSettled([p1, p2, p3])
  .then(results => {
    console.log(results);
  });


ğŸ“Œ Output:

[
  { status: "fulfilled", value: "âœ… Success 1" },
  { status: "rejected", reason: "âŒ Failed 2" },
  { status: "fulfilled", value: "âœ… Success 3" }
]

ğŸ”¹ When to use Promise.allSettled?

âœ… When you need results of all promises, even if some fail.

âœ… Good for tasks like loading multiple API calls, where you still want partial results.

